		{
			"role": "section",
			"layout": "bodyContainerLayout",
			"style": "bodyContainerStyle",
			"anchor": {
				"targetAnchorPosition": "top"
			},
			"components": [
				{
					"role": "intro",
					"layout": "dateLayout",
					"text": "Aug 5, 2015 @ 6:01 PM",
					"textStyle": "dateStyle"
				},
				{
					"role": "title",
					"layout": "titleLayout",
					"text": "The Rebuilding of the _Panama Canal_, in Pictures",
					"textStyle": "titleStyle",
					"format": "markdown"
				},
				{
					"role": "intro",
					"layout": "introLayout",
					"text": "The great canal, now a century old, must be widened to fit today's megaships.",
					"textStyle": "introStyle"
				},
				{
					"role": "divider",
					"stroke": {
						"color": "#FFF0"
					},
					"layout": "blackStrokeLayout1",
					"style": "baseStrokeStyle"
				},
				{
					"role": "author",
					"layout": "authorLayout",
					"text": "By Kevin Dupzyk",
					"textStyle": "authorStyle"
				},
				{
					"role": "divider",
					"stroke": {
						"color": "#FFF0"
					},
					"layout": "blackStrokeLayout1",
					"style": "baseStrokeStyle"
				},
				{ 
					 "role": "medium_rectangle_advertisement",
					 "layout": "adLayout",
					 "bannerType": "standard"
				},
				{
					"role": "body",
					"text": "In 1984 about a million tons of cargo passed through the Suez Canal every day. Last year that number was up to 2.6 million. Over the same period, the number of ships traversing the canal every year dropped, from more than 21,000 to about 17,000. How? The ships got bigger. The highest-capacity container ship at sea today holds more than four times as much cargo as the record holder in 1984. With global demand for imported goods increasing, companies employ the cost-effective strategy of cramming everything on large vessels and making fewer trips.",
					"layout": "bodyLayout",
					"textStyle": "bodyStyleFirst",
					"format": "markdown"
				},
				{
					"role": "section",
					"layout": "slideLayout",
					"components": [
						{
							"role": "heading",
							"text": "The Atlantic Locks",
							"layout": "heading1Layout",
							"textStyle": "heading1Style",
							"format": "markdown"
						},
						{
							"role": "container",
							"style": "photoContainerStyle",
							"components": [
								{
									"role": "image",
									"URL": "http://pop.h-cdn.co/assets/15/32/1024x1536/gallery-1438634014-panama-lede.jpg",
									"layout": "photoLayout",
									"animation": {
										"type": "fade_in",
										"userControllable": true,
										"initialAlpha": 0.1
									}
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"role": "photographer",
							"text": "Tom Fowlks",
							"layout": "creditLayout",
							"textStyle": "creditStyle"
						},			
						{
							"role": "caption",
							"text": "The Atlantic locks, looking toward the ocean. When construction is complete, the plug of dirt at the bottom of the picture will be removed and water will flow through.",
							"layout": "captionLayout",
							"textStyle": "captionStyle",
							"format": "markdown"
						}
					]
				},
				{
					"role": "section",
					"layout": "slideLayout",
					"components": [
						{
							"role": "heading",
							"text": "The Pacific Lock Complex",
							"layout": "heading1Layout",
							"textStyle": "heading1Style",
							"format": "markdown"
						},
						{
							"role": "container",
							"style": "photoContainerStyle",
							"components": [
								{
									"role": "image",
									"URL": "http://pop.h-cdn.co/assets/15/32/1024x682/panama-01.jpg",
									"layout": "photoLayout",
									"animation": {
										"type": "fade_in",
										"userControllable": true,
										"initialAlpha": 0.1
									}
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"role": "photographer",
							"text": "Tom Fowlks",
							"layout": "creditLayout",
							"textStyle": "creditStyle"
						},			
						{
							"role": "caption",
							"text": "The Pacific lock complex, looking into the interior of the isthmus. The camera is planted on the bit of dirt that keeps the ocean out of the canal-in-progress. Workers call it el tapon, which is Spanish for \"cork\" or \"stopper.\"",
							"layout": "captionLayout",
							"textStyle": "captionStyle",
							"format": "markdown"
						}
					]
				},
				{
					"role": "section",
					"layout": "slideLayout",
					"components": [
						{
							"role": "heading",
							"text": "Nearing Completion",
							"layout": "heading1Layout",
							"textStyle": "heading1Style",
							"format": "markdown"
						},
						{
							"role": "container",
							"style": "photoContainerStyle",
							"components": [
								{
									"role": "image",
									"URL": "http://pop.h-cdn.co/assets/15/32/1024x1303/panama-02.jpg",
									"layout": "photoLayout",
									"animation": {
										"type": "fade_in",
										"userControllable": true,
										"initialAlpha": 0.1
									}
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"role": "photographer",
							"text": "Tom Fowlks",
							"layout": "creditLayout",
							"textStyle": "creditStyle"
						},			
						{
							"role": "caption",
							"text": "The Pacific lock complex under construction. With the work nearly complete, cranes have started to be dismantled.",
							"layout": "captionLayout",
							"textStyle": "captionStyle",
							"format": "markdown"
						}
					]
				},
				{
					"role": "banner_advertisement",
					"bannerType": "standard"
				}
			]
		}
	],
